From Wiktionary, the free dictionary

Spanish

[edit]

Alternative forms

[edit]
  • executar (obsolete)

Etymology

[edit]

Borrowed from Medieval Latin executāre, from exsecūtus, perfect passive participle of exsequor, from ex- (“out”) + sequor (“to follow”). Ex- becomes ej- in Spanish orthography. Cognate with Portuguese executar, French exécuter, English execute, Italian eseguire.

Pronunciation

[edit]
  • IPA(key): /exekuˈtaɾ/ [e.xe.kuˈt̪aɾ]
  • Rhymes: -aɾ
  • Syllabification: e‧je‧cu‧tar

Verb

[edit]

ejecutar (first-person singular present ejecuto, first-person singular preterite ejecuté, past participle ejecutado)

  1. to execute, to run (enact or carry out)
  2. to execute (carry out a death sentence)
  3. to perform (a piece of music, a dance, etc.)
